<HL>
   Goldman Is Sued
   Over a Data Base
   By CPM Group
   ----
   By William Power
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/11/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C13
</SO>
<IN>
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
PRECIOUS METALS, STONES, GOLD, SILVER (PCS)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Goldman, Sachs &amp; Co. was hit with another
lawsuit centering on the investment banking firm's commodity
operations.
   Goldman was sued for $9 million by its former
commodity-research group, which is now an independent company
called CPM Group. In a complaint filed in New York state
Supreme Court in Manhattan, CPM claims that Goldman destroyed
a major data base on gold, silver and platinum trends that
CPM and Goldman had shared, in what the suit alleges was a
"conspiracy and scheme" to hurt Goldman competitors.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The CPM suit is the second to be filed recently that
focuses on Goldman's large commodity operations. In December,
the former head of Goldman Sachs's oil-futures unit, Leo
Haviland, alleged in a suit in federal court in Manhattan
that he was forced out of his $600,000-a-year job after he
refused Goldman partners' "repeated attempts to extort" him
into divulging confidential information. The suit claimed the
information was about customer accounts, so that the partners
could benefit through Goldman's J. Aron commodity-trading
division.
   Although unrelated, both the Haviland suit and the new one
accuse Goldman of misusing its power to gain advantage in the
markets.
   Goldman has vigorously denied the allegations in the
Haviland suit. And in an answer to the CPM suit filed in
state court, Goldman denies CPM's allegations and asks that
the suit be dismissed. A Goldman spokesman said: "This is a
minor contractual dispute over access to our own library
materials, which in any event the former consultant had no
right to following the termination of the contract in
November 1989."
   CPM, run by former Goldman Vice President Jeffrey M.
Christian, is a consultant and research firm based in New
York. Originally an arm of Goldman, the firm went independent
in 1986, and its clients included, until last year, Goldman
itself. Early this month, the Silver Institute, a trade
group, announced it hired CPM to produce statistical reviews
of the international silver market. CPM also advises mining
companies.
   The CPM suit alleges that Goldman and Goldman partner
Dennis Suskind reneged on an agreement to maintain the big
precious-metal data base, including research files,
periodicals and books. CPM said Goldman was obligated to
maintain the data base and allow CPM to use it, even if CPM's
consulting agreement with Goldman ran out. But the suit
claims the data base was "thrown out and destroyed" without
notice.
   Mr. Suskind declined to comment on the CPM suit beyond the
spokesman's statement.
   CPM is seeking $4 million in damages, mostly for lost
business, and $5 million in punitive damages.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900511-0155
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900511-0155.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Credit Ratings:
   Credit Ratings
   Of 3 Bank Firms
   Are Cut by S&amp;P
   ----
   By David Stipp
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/11/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   NEB FNG BKB
</CO>
<IN>
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
BANKS (BNK)
CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
</IN>
<LP>
   Standard &amp; Poor's Corp. said it lowered its ratings on the
senior debt of Bank of New England Corp., Bank of Boston
Corp. and Fleet/Norstar Financial Group because of the
worsening New England economy, particularly its real estate
sector.
   S&amp;P said it lowered its ratings on $820 million of Bank of
Boston's debt. Among the issues affected were the
Boston-based company's senior debt, whose rating was lowered
to triple-B-minus from triple-B-plus; subordinated debt,
downgraded to double-B-plus from triple-B; preferred stock,
lowered to double-B from triple-B-minus; and commercial
paper, reduced to A-3 from A-2.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The Bank of Boston issues were removed from CreditWatch,
where they were placed April 30 with negative implications,
S&amp;P added.
   S&amp;P said Bank of Boston's first-quarter results "evidence
the company's slide in asset quality and continued deepening
of the New England regional real estate recession." S&amp;P added
that the company's loan-loss provisions haven't "kept pace
with problem loan identification, and it is likely that lower
profitability in future quarters will result."
   Peter J. Manning, Bank of Boston's chief financial
officer, said that the company is "obviously disappointed" at
the rating change, and that "we stand ready to deal with
uncertainties in the current economic environment."
   For the first quarter, Bank of Boston earned $43.6
million, or 56 cents a share, compared with $89.1 million, or
$1.23 a share, a year earlier.
   S&amp;P said it lowered its ratings on Bank of New England's
senior debt to triple-C from single-B-plus and on its
subordinated debt to double-C from single-B-minus. About $675
million of debt was affected by the rating changes, S&amp;P
added.
   S&amp;P said the Boston-based bank-holding company "has made
strides in coping with its difficult operating environment,
especially in stabilizing its immediate liquidity troubles,
but its viability is dependent on improvement in the regional
economy and continued regulatory forbearance." S&amp;P added that
"given a stringent regulatory environment and general
illiquidity of the parent company, it is likely that bank
holding company creditors will suffer losses."
   For the first quarter, Bank of New England reported a loss
of $46.6 million, or 68 cents a share, including a $124.8
million pretax gain from the sale of assets.
   In Boston, a Bank of New England spokesman said the S&amp;P
downgrade "is not unexpected." He added that the concern "is
current on all of its interest payments. Deposits have
stabilized, and the company is moving forward with its
recovery plan."
   S&amp;P said it lowered its ratings on Fleet/Norstar Financial
Group's senior debt to single-A-minus from single-A-plus,
subordinated debt to triple-B-plus from single-A, preferred
stock to triple-B from single-A-minus, and commercial paper
to A-2 from A-1.
   The issues were removed from CreditWatch, where they were
placed Monday with negative implications, S&amp;P said. About
$2.2 billion of debt was affected.
   S&amp;P said "the downgrades reflect Fleet/Norstar's poor
first-quarter results and substantial rise in nonperforming
assets, which confirm that the New England regional economic
troubles, especially in real estate, have not abated."
   In Providence, R.I., Jack Flynn, Fleet/Norstar's vice
president, finance, said, "We're pleased S&amp;P continues to
rank our {senior} debt in the A category."
   For the first quarter, Fleet/Norstar reported a loss of
$98.1 million, or 92 cents a share.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
