<IN>
MORTGAGES, MORTGAGE BANKERS, MORTGAGE-BACKED SECURITIES (MOR)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
</IN>
<LP>
   The following were among yesterday's offerings and
pricings in U.S. and non-U.S. capital markets, with terms and
syndicate manager, as compiled by Dow Jones Capital Markets
Report:
                                                                                                       

                      MUNICIPALS
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   New York City -- the bulk of $900 million of general
obligation revenue anticipation notes, Fiscal 1990 Series C
and D, due June 29, 1990, apparently was won by a Merrill
Lynch Capital Markets group. Merrill Lynch purchased $400
million in notes at yields ranging from 6.247% to 6.419%. The
notes were priced as follows: $100 million of notes priced to
yield 6.247%, $50 million of notes priced to yield 6.288%,
$100 million of notes priced to yield 6.337%, $100 million of
notes priced to yield 6.386% and $50 million of notes priced
to yield 6.419%. The notes, rated MIG-2 by Moody's Investors
Service Inc. and SP-1 by Standard &amp; Poor's Corp., were priced
at the initial reoffering to yield 6.40%, according to an
official with the lead underwriter. The notes are being sold
to help the city meet its financial obligations until it
receives funds from the state. The state funds are
unavailable until a state budget is passed. All together,
seven firms purchased the $900 million in notes, according to
city officials.
                                                                                                       

                         MORTGAGES
                                                                                                       

   Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. -- $153 million of Shearson
Lehman Hutton Mortgage Trust real estate mortgage investment
conduit securities is being offered in eight classes. Full
pricing details weren't immediately available. The offering,
Trust 1, is backed by 15-year and 30-year mortgages with a
weighted average coupon rate of 10.97%. The mortgages are
"non-conforming," which means they aren't eligible for
purchase by the Federal National Mortgage Association or
Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp. Most of the mortgages are
too large to be purchased by either agency. The issue is
rated triple-A by Moody's Investors Service Inc. and Standard
&amp; Poor's Corp. based on the quality of the underlying loans,
which are mostly from California, and an insurance policy
covering 10% of the deal from General Electric Mortgage
Insurance Co.
                                                                                                       

                        EUROBONDS
                                                                                                       

   World Bank (agency) -- 200 million marks ($122.3 million)
of 8 7/8% bonds due June 1, 2000, priced at 101 5/8 to yield
8.62%, via Bayerische Landesbank Girozentrale. Also 100
million Australian dollars (US$75.6 million) of 14 1/2% bonds
due June 7, 1996, priced at 102 to yield 14.47% less fees,
via Hambros Bank. Fees 1 7/8.
   Autobahnen &amp; Schnellstrassen-Finanzierungs-
Aktiengesellschaft (Austria) -- 150 million Swiss francs
($107.1 million) of 7 1/4% public bonds due June 25, 2000,
priced at 7 1/4% via Swiss Bank Corp. Guaranteed by the
Republic of Austria.
   Okobank (Finland) -- 10 billion yen ($64 million) of 7.4%
bonds due May 22, 1995, priced at 101 7/8, via Nomura
International. Call option at par on May 22, 1992.
   Cellular Inc. (U.S.) -- $40 million of 8% convertible
subordinated debentures due 2000, priced at par, via Kidder,
Peabody International Ltd. The debentures are convertible at
any time prior to maturity into shares of the company's
common stock on or after the date on which definitive
debentures are issued in exchange for the temporary global
debenture. The conversion price will be $14.95 per share,
subject to adjustment under certain circumstances. The
company also said the debentures are redeemable at the option
of the company at any time after the expiration of 30 days
following the date on which the temporary global debenture is
exchanged for definitive debentures, at prices declining from
106%, if called prior to May 18, 1991, to 100% on or after
May 18, 1996. The debentures aren't redeemable prior to May
18, 1993, unless the closing price of the common stock for a
specified period is at least 200% of the conversion price
then in effect. Proceeds will be used to finance acquisitions
of cellular telephone properties.
   Canton of Bern (Switzerland) -- 51 million Swiss francs of
bonds due June 1, 2000, with equity-purchase warrants, fixed
5 3/4% coupon at par, via Citicorp Investment Bank
Switzerland. Exercise period of warrants from June 1, 1990,
to Dec. 1, 1991. Each 6,800 franc bond issued with one
warrant allowing the right to acquire one basket of shares of
Swiss chemical companies consisting of one Sandoz Ltd.
registered share, four Ciba-Geigy Ltd. registered shares and
six La Roche Holding participation certificates at a price of
45,945 francs, an 18.6% premium to Wednesday's closing
prices.
