<HL>
   U.S. Reduces Duties
   On Colombian Flowers
</HL>
<DATE>
05/11/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   LATAM
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
</IN>
<GV>
COMMERCE DEPARTMENT (COM)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The Commerce Department reduced anti-dumping
duties for cut flowers imported from Colombia.
   Officials said the department had overestimated the extent
to which the imports are "dumped" -- that is sold at prices
below those in the home market or the cost of production --
when it first imposed 4.4% duties in 1987. The duties will
drop to 4.16% on some flowers and to 2.24% on others. The
imports -- mostly carnations, chrysanthemums and pompons --
are valued at about $180 million a year.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Colombia has protested that the duties undermine anti-drug
efforts by injuring legitimate farmers. A lawyer for the
Colombian growers said the reduction in the duties "is an
important victory for us."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
