   Business Brief -- British Petroleum PLC:
   Earnings Are Down by 43%;
   Inventory Losses Are Factor
</HL>
<DATE>
05/11/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   BP
</CO>
<IN>
OIL, SECONDARY (OIS)
PETROLEUM (PET)
EARNINGS (ERN)
DIVIDENDS (DIV)
</IN>
<LP>
   British Petroleum PLC registered a 43% plunge in
first-quarter profit, with depressed chemical earnings and
inventory losses countering strong growth in exploration and
production.
   First-quarter sales advanced 36%.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Britain's biggest oil company saw net in the quarter drop
to #344 million ($578 million) from #608 million ($1.02
billion) the year earlier. These figures are on a
historic-cost basis, which values inventories at the cost of
acquisition. They include a #19 million inventory loss,
compared with a #234 million gain a year earlier.
   Per-share earnings dropped 38% to 6.4 pence (10.7 cents)
from 10.3 pence.
   On a replacement-cost basis, which excludes the effect of
inventory gains or losses, net fell a more modest 5.2% to
#361 million from #381 million.
   Sales jumped to #8.86 billion from #6.53 billion.
   Despite the earnings slide, the company said it would
increase its first-quarter dividend to 3.95 pence from 3.65
pence.
