</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900511-0020.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Fairchild Industries Unit Is Charged
   With Producing Fake Data on Jet Parts
   ----
   By Michael Allen
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/11/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4
</SO>
<CO>
   BA BNR
</CO>
<IN>
INDUSTRIAL EQUIPMENT, MACHINE TOOLS (IND)
AEROSPACE (ARO)
</IN>
<GV>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
</GV>
<LP>
   A Fairchild Industries Inc. unit systematically generated
fraudulent testing documents for special nuts, bolts and
other fasteners used on most U.S. commercial jetliners and
military aircraft, federal prosecutors charged.
   The charges stem from an investigation following a weekend
raid in February 1989 of Fairchild's VSI Corp. fastener plant
in California by about 20 agents of the Federal Bureau of
Investigation and the Defense Criminal Investigative Service.
Agents hauled away about 50 boxes of fasteners and documents
as part of an extensive inquiry into allegations of fraud in
the aerospace-parts industry.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The charges, brought against Fairchild's Voi-Shan testing
laboratory in Chatsworth, Calif., and two of its managers,
are contained in a complaint filed earlier this week in
federal court in Seattle by Assistant U.S. Attorney Bruce D.
Carter.
   According to the complaint, a phantom "Inspector 11" at
the California plant was part of a 15-year scheme to falsify
test reports submitted to the government. Affidavits
supporting the complaint said the No. 11 inspector's stamp
wasn't assigned to any employee, but instead was used
routinely to indicate that parts had passed inspection, even
when tests hadn't been performed.
   In a statement filed in court along with the indictment,
Mr. Carter said some inadequate Voi-Shan parts were found,
but investigators still don't know if there is any imminent
air-safety concern from untested or possibly defective parts
used years earlier on aircraft flying today. "No accidents
have been traced to Voi-Shan bolts," he said in the
statement.
   Voi-Shan is the largest of Fairchild's three fastener
operations. The unit makes pins and collars, lock bolts,
rivets, nuts and other special fastener products. Some bolts
made at the plant are intended to bear loads exceeding
200,000 pounds per square inch. Customers include such major
aircraft and engine manufacturers as Boeing Co., McDonnell
Douglas Corp., Lockheed Corp., General Electric Co. and
United Technologies Corp.'s Pratt &amp; Whitney Co. unit.
   At Fairchild headquarters in Chantilly, Va., a spokeswoman
said she couldn't comment on the charges, because the company
is negotiating with the Justice Department to "resolve" the
civil and criminal allegations. "We believe a resolution is
imminent," she said.
   The spokeswoman also said Fairchild is confident that the
quality of its products has never jeopardized air safety. She
indicated that Fairchild would issue an additional statement
today after a court hearing in Seattle on the matter.
   According to the charges, the investigation of Voi-Shan
was prompted by a complaint from a whistleblower, Thomas
Runion, shortly after he left his job in the metallurgical
laboratory at the Chatsworth plant.
   The complaint also names as defendants James E. Ryan, a
former Voi-Shan quality-assurance manager, and Aram
Marderian, a former metallurgical lab supervisor for
Voi-Shan. If convicted, each faces a maximum sentence of five
years in prison and a $250,000 fine.
   Neither man could be reached for comment.
   The Fairchild unit and the former employees are charged
with conspiracy to commit mail fraud, to make false
statements to the government and to cheat the U.S. According
to court documents, the object of the alleged conspiracy was
to hold down costs of inspection and testing in order to
boost the unit's profits.
   The documents cite dozens of instances in which Voi-Shan
allegedly failed to conduct tests of strength, durability and
brittleness, and yet produced reports approved by the
fictitious inspector indicating that such tests had been
properly performed.
   Nevertheless, court documents indicate, Voi-Shan allegedly
shipped parts that were later rejected by aircraft makers
which subjected the products to their own testing procedures.
According to an affidavit, Fairchild also shipped some parts
that had rusted in a salt-spray test.
   Eight other defendants already have pleaded guilty in the
case, prosecutors said, and the investigation is continuing.
   In a prepared statement, Boeing said its use of Voi-Shan
materials "has not compromised the integrity of Boeing
products."
   Comments from other major Voi-Shan customers weren't
immediately available.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900511-0019
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900511-0019.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   How Stock-Picking
   By Firms Is Judged
   In Quarterly Review
</HL>
<DATE>
05/11/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C5
</SO>
<CO>
   MER RJF SLH AXP PA PWJ AGE S
</CO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Within reason, brokerage houses in the
Journal-Zacks study of stock-picking prowess may choose the
list of stocks on which they will be judged. (Of course, they
must specify in advance.)
   Merrill Lynch, PaineWebber and Raymond James are judged by
the stocks their analysts rate "1" on a five-point scale.
Kidder Peabody is judged by stocks rated "1"or "2." A.G.
Edwards is judged by stocks analysts say to "buy" or
"accumulate."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Starting at the end of January, Prudential-Bache began
publishing a weekly list giving each analyst's "single best
idea." It's judged on that, with sell ideas excluded. (For
January it was judged on stocks rated "1" for either short or
long term, and no lower than "2" for any term.)
   At four firms -- Dean Witter, Goldman Sachs, Shearson and
Smith Barney, a stock-selection committee reviews analysts'
recommendations and picks a select group of stocks as the
firm's official recommended list. Those firms are judged on
the committee's list.
   The study assumes that an investor buys the recommended
stocks, and sells all others, even if they're designated as
holds or weak buys. Equal dollar amounts are put into each
stock, and portfolios are adjusted monthly to keep the
amounts equal. All buying and selling is on the last trading
day of each month. Commissions and taxes are disregarded,
mostly to make the results comparable to market indexes.
Dividends are included.
   Brokerage houses are given a chance to check the data for
accuracy. All 10 firms did so this quarter.
   (See related story: "Pru-Bache Tops Big Firms in
First-Quarter Stock Picks" -- WSJ May 11, 1990)
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900511-0018
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900511-0018.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Money-Fund Assets
   Fell by $2.22 Billion
</HL>
<DATE>
05/11/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C5
</SO>
<IN>
MUTUAL AND MONEY-MARKET FUNDS (FND)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Assets of the nation's 508 money-market funds
fell $2.22 billion, to $383.50 billion, in the week ended
Wednesday, according to the Investment Company Institute, a
trade association.
   Assets of 246 general-purpose funds fell $531.6 million,
to $132.17 billion, while assets of 102 broker-dealer funds
fell $854.3 million, to $159.84 billion. Assets of 160
institutional funds fell $831.2 million, to $91.48 billion.
Mutual-fund assets revised for the week ending May 2 fell
$2.15 billion, to $385.71 billion.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "Yields on money-market funds changed very little during
the week," said Jacob Dreyer, vice president and chief
economist at the Washington-based institute. But yields on
direct money-market instruments were "quite volatile," he
said. "These changing relationships may have prompted money
managers, as well as individuals to engage in asset
shuffling."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900511-0017
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900511-0017.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   What's News --
   World-Wide
</HL>
<DATE>
05/11/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   NATO MOVED toward a restructuring of the West's
nuclear-weapons strategy.
   Concluding a two-day meeting in Canada, the alliance's
defense ministers said that because of recent political
changes in Eastern Europe there is a "diminishing need" for
short-range nuclear arms in NATO's arsenal, opening the way
for deep reductions in its battlefield weapons. The Western
officials also called on the Soviet Union to make
"substantial" unilateral cuts in its short-range nuclear
missile systems. A full NATO summit is set for July 5-6 in
London.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   NATO and the Warsaw Pact failed to meet a target date for
a pact on mutual surveillance of airspace, citing superpower
differences on the overflights.
   ---
   China announced the release of 211 prisoners, including
several prominent intellectuals, who were arrested after last
year's crackdown on pro-democracy protests. Diplomats and
others said the move appeared aimed at derailing efforts by
U.S. lawmakers to strip China of most-favored nation trade
status.
   ---
   The House approved a bill granting workers as much as 12
weeks of unpaid annual leave to care for newborn or adopted
children or seriously ill family members. But the 237-187
vote fell short of the two-thirds majority needed to override
a predicted presidential veto. The measure goes to the
Senate.
   ---
   The Senate voted to allow federal civilservice and postal
workers to take a more active role in partisan politics.
Ignoring a threatened Bush veto, the chamber approved a
revision of the 1939 Hatch Act, which bars 2.9 million
government employees from participating in campaigns.
   ---
   Washington's Mayor Barry was indicted on six additional
drug charges alleging that he possessed cocaine on several
occasions from the fall of 1984 until his arrest last January
in an FBI sting operation. The 54-year-old official was first
indicted in February on charges of cocaine possession and
lying to a grand jury. He has pleaded innocent.
   ---
   A federal appeals court ruled that New York's Metropolitan
Transportation Authority can prohibit begging in the city's
subway system. The ruling overturned a lower court decision
blocking enforcement of rules against begging. The earlier
ruling had characterized begging and panhandling as forms of
free speech.
   ---
   Estonia proposed establishing a council of officials from
the three Baltic republics to coordinate policies as they
seek independence from the Soviet Union. The call was made as
the three republics implemented an agricultural pact that
allows them to bypass Moscow. Lithuania, meanwhile, took
control of its TV and radio, defying the Kremlin.
   ---
   About 100,000 East Germans protested possible job and
housing losses following German reunification, staging
strikes and blocking roads. The demonstrations came as
Premier de Maiziere, speaking before East Berlin's
legislature, portrayed a rapidly deteriorating economy.
                                                                                                       

   West German Chancellor Kohl pressed East Germany for
greater flexibility in bargaining over the merger of their
economies, planned by July 2. He also warned that there must
be an accord on revamping the East German economy before its
currency can be converted in West German marks.
   ---
   Poland dissolved the country's long-feared secret police
as part of a move to place law-enforcement agencies under
civilian control. In Gdansk, Solidarity founder Walesa
criticized the government for failing to resolve the status
of the city's shipyard, where the labor union began nearly 10
years ago and which is threatened to be closed.
   ---
   South Korean dissidents defied a government warning
against violence, engaging in street battles with riot police
in Seoul and other cities for a second consecutive day. The
protesters demanded that President Roh annul a merger of his
ruling party with two opposition groups, a move completed in
January, and that he resign.
   ---
   South Africa's de Klerk met with French President
Mitterrand in Paris, and urged European nations to lift
sanctions against the Pretoria government. The talks, part of
a nine-nation tour by de Klerk, are aimed at convincing
Western leaders that South Africa is serious about ending
apartheid.
   ---
   The State Department is recalling the U.S. envoy to
Romania as an expression of concern about acts of
intimidation against opposition candidates running in May 20
elections. The decision came amid allegations by
anti-Communist demonstrators that the electoral process is
being manipulated by Bucharest's interim government.
   ---
   A Senate panel's report estimated that 2.2 million
Americans -- about one of every 100 -- use cocaine at least
once a week, more than double the official count of
"hard-core" users. On a state-by-state basis, the Judiciary
Committee said New York leads with one regular user for every
40 residents.
   ---
   Died: Walker Percy, 74, writer whose novels, such as "The
Moviegoer," and essays explored alienation and redemption in
the South, in Covington, La., of cancer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
