<HL>
   CAE Profit Plunged
   94% in Fiscal Year;
   U.S. Results Cited
</HL>
<DATE>
05/11/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   T.CAE
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   TORONTO -- CAE Industries Ltd. said lower earnings from
the company's U.S. operations and accounting changes resulted
in a 94% drop in net income for the year ended March 31.
   CAE, a dominant player in the military and commercial
simulation markets, reported net income of 2.7 million
Canadian dollars (US$2.3 million) or three cents (Cdn) a
share, in the 1990 fiscal year, down from C$42.8 million, or
55 cents (Cdn) a share, the previous year. Revenue rose 33%
to C$1.12 billion from C$838.8 million.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   CAE attributed the decline to changes in accounting
practices, which increased the company's income taxes and the
amount of a write-down on two unprofitable contracts at its
U.S. operations, CAELink. Income taxes payable in fiscal 1990
rose to C$19.1 million from C$11.7 million in 1989. The
write-down, originally estimated at C$10.5 million, now
amounts to C$17.5 million.
   Interest expenses also rose by C$15 million to C$42.9
million.
   CAE said that without the accounting changes, the company
would have reported net of about 30 cents (Cdn) a share.
   CAE acquired Singer Co.'s Link Flight Simulation Division
in 1988 for $550 million. The company has embarked on a
restructuring program which CAE's senior vice president of
finance, John Caldwell, said will improve the unit's
profitability in a few years' time.
   David Race, the company's president and chief executive
officer, said he expects to see "modest growth" in revenue
and profitability in its fiscal 1991 year. He declined to
give a specific estimate.
   "Based on the . . . progress we expect to make this year,
I am optimistic that fiscal 1992 should show a return to
improved growth in revenue and earnings," Mr. Race said.
</TEXT>
